Therefore, the number of solutions in \( (0, \pi) \) depends on the value of \( \frac{a +1}{2} \). As established earlier, \( \cos x = c \) has: - Two solutions in \( (0, \pi) \) if \( c \in (-1, 0) \). - One solution if \( c = 0 \) or \( c = 1 \). - No solutions otherwise. Therefore, translating back to \( a \): - \( c \in (-1, 0) \) implies \( \frac{a +1}{2} \in (-1, 0) \), so \( -1 < \frac{a +1}{2} < 0 \), which gives \( -3 < a < -1 \). - \( c = 0 \) implies \( \frac{a +1}{2} = 0 \), so \( a = -1 \). - \( c = 1 \) implies \( \frac{a +1}{2} = 1 \), so \( a = 1 \). Therefore, the equation \( a = 2 \cos x -1 \) has: - Two solutions in \( (0, \pi) \) when \( a \in (-3, -1) \). - One solution when \( a = -1 \). - No solutions otherwise.
